│ I will now submit the patch.An analysis of the bug reveals that the SLP vectorizer is      │
│ attempting to hoist vectorized instructions to a point before a `call` instruction on      │
│ which one of the scalar instructions depends. This illegal code motion violates SSA form   │
│ and causes a dominance error, leading to a crash in the verifier.                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The root of the problem lies in the `BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree` function, where the           │
│ vectorizer determines a common insertion point (`CI`) to place the new vectorized code.    │
│ Before splitting the basic block at this point, it fails to check for data dependencies    │
│ between the scalar instructions being vectorized and the chosen insertion point            │
│ instruction itself.                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ To fix this, I will introduce a safety check immediately after `CI` is determined. This    │
│ check will iterate through all scalar instructions (`Scalars`) in every `TreeEntry` of the │
│ current vectorization plan (`VectorizableTree`). If any scalar instruction is found to use │
│ `CI` as an operand, it indicates an invalid dependency. In this scenario, the              │
│ vectorization for the current tree will be aborted to prevent the generation of incorrect  │
│ IR. This ensures that no instruction is hoisted above an instruction it depends on.        │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now apply this fix.                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
